ized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Maoil Mhín</b> ‘descendant of the devotee of Maoilmhín’, a personal name meaning ‘gentle chieftain’."]},{"name":"Mulville","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Melville  ."]},{"name":"Mellin","meanings":["Scottish (Glamorgan): variant of   Melville  .","German: habitational name from any of various places so called.","English: variant of   Melling  ."]},{"name":"Mulvihill","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Paddy.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Maoil Mhichíl</b> ‘descendant of the devotee of (Saint) Michael’. The Anglicized form was sometimes abbreviated into   Melville  ."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Walter Melville was born in 1250, in Peeblesshire, Scotland as the son of Stephen Melville, Lord of Melville. He had at least 1 son with Melville."},"et":{"1250–":"1250–Surnud","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1287–1345":"1287–1345","1212–Male":"1212–Surnud","1345":"1345","1212":"1212","1287":"1287","1250":"1250","Peeblesshire, Scotland":"Peeblesshire, Scotland","Melville, Lasswade, Midlothian, Scotland":"Lasswade, Midlothian, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1250–":"1250–Kuollut","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1287–1345":"1287–1345","1212–Male":"1212–Kuollut","1345":"1345","1212":"1212","1287":"1287","1250":"1250","Peeblesshire, Scotland":"P